iel \u00c5hs.jpg|[[Charlotte Perrelli|Charlotte Nilsson]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1999|1999]] contest for Sweden.\nFile:Olsen Brothers.jpg|[[Olsen Brothers]], winners of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2000|2000]] contest for Denmark.\nFile:Dave Benton.jpg|[[Dave Benton]], winner (together with [[Tanel Padar]] and [[Soul Militia|2XL]]) of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2001|2001]] contest for Estonia.\nFile:Maria Naumova 2.JPG|[[Marie N]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2002|2002]] contest for Latvia.\nFile:Sertab Erener (cropped).jpg|[[Sertab Erener]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]] contest for Turkey.\nFile:Ruslana, 2009-05-09 (2).jpg|[[Ruslana]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]] contest for Ukraine.\nFile:Paparizou HBH Fruitea.jpg|[[Elena Paparizou|Helena Paparizou]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005]] contest for Greece.\nFile:MrLordi2013.jpg|[[Lordi]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2006|2006]] contest for Finland.\nFile:Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107.jpg|[[Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]] contest for Serbia.\nFile:Dima Bilan 2008 Eurovision 2.jpg|[[Dima Bilan]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]] contest for Russia.\nFile:Alexander Rybak at the Eurovision press conference.jpg|[[Alexander Rybak]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]] contest for Norway.\nFile:Lena Meyer-Landrut at PC after 2010 Eurovision 2.jpg|[[Lena Meyer-Landrut|Lena]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2010|2010]] contest for Germany.\nFile:Ell & Nikki - Azerbaijan (Eurovision Song Contest 2011) cropped 2.jpg|[[Ell & Nikki]], winners of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011]] contest for Azerbaijan.\nFile:Loreen Eurovision 2012 winner.jpg|[[Loreen (singer)|Loreen]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]] contest for Sweden.\nFile:ESC2013 winner's press conference 06 (crop).jpg|[[Emmelie de Forest]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]] contest for Denmark.\nFile:ESC2014 winner's press conference 11 (crop).jpg|[[Conchita Wurst]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]] contest for Austria.\nFile:20150514 ESC 2015 M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w 5767.jpg|[[M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015]] contest for Sweden.\nFile:ESC2016 winner's press conference 02 (cropped).jpg|[[Jamala]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]] contest for Ukraine.\nFile:Salvador Sobral RedCarpet Kyiv 2017.jpg|[[Salvador Sobral]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]] contest for Portugal.\nFile:Netta (3) 20180508 EuroVisionary (cropped).jpg|[[Netta Barzilai|Netta]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]] contest for Israel.\nFile:Duncan Laurence with the 2019 Eurovision Trophy.jpg|[[Duncan Laurence]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2019|2019]] contest for the Netherlands.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Eurovision Song Contest winning songwriters]]\n* [[Eurovision Song Contest winners discography]]\n* [[List of Junior Eurovision Song Contest winners]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{Commons category|Winners of the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n* [http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history Eurovision Song Contest history]. Eurovision.tv. Retrieved on 19 August 2007.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070817062852/http://www.esctoday.com/annual/contests.php?section=history History]. ESCtoday.com. Retrieved on 19 August 2007.\n* John Kennedy O'Connor (2005). ''The Eurovision Song Contest 50 Years The Official History''. London: Carlton Books Limited. {{ISBN|1-84442-586-X}}.\n\n{{Eurovision years}}\n{{List of Eurovision Song Contest winners}}\n{{Featured list}}\n\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest winners|*]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest related lists|Winners]]\n[[Category:Lists of award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia talk:Featured lists]] for an explanation of this and other inclusion tags below -->\n{{multiple image\n| footer = '''Left:''' [[Lys Assia]], the first Eurovision winner (1956), and [[Dima Bilan]], winner in 2008. '''Centre:''' [[Johnny Logan (singer)|Johnny Logan]], the winning artist in 1980, winning artist and composer in 1987 and the winning composer in 1992. '''Right:''' [[Loreen (singer)|Loreen]] celebrating her [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012]] victory in [[Baku]].\n| width1    = 200\n| image1    = Lys Assia and Dima Bilan 2009.jpg\n| width2    = 125\n| image2    = Donauinselfest 20090628 Johnny Logan 025.jpg\n| width3    = 97\n| image3    = Loreen_Eurovision_2012_winner.jpg\n}}\n\nSixty-seven songs have won the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], an annual competition organised by member countries of the [[European Broadcasting Union]]. The contest, which has been broadcast every year since its debut in 1956, is one of the longest-running television programmes in the world. The contest's winner has been determined using numerous [[Voting at the Eurovision Song Contest|voting techniques]] throughout its history; centre to these have been the awarding of points to countries by juries or [[televoting|televoters]]. The country awarded the most points is declared the winner.<ref>[http://www.eurovision.tv/addons/files/Extract_ESC2007Rules.pdf Extract from the rules for the 2007 Eurovision Song Contest]. Eurovision.tv. Retrieved on 22 August 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070507234645/http://www.eurovision.tv/addons/files/Extract_ESC2007Rules.pdf |date=May 7, 2007 }}</ref> The first Eurovision Song Contest was not won on points, but by votes (two per country), and only the winner was announced.<ref>[http://www.eurovision.tv/index/main?page=66&event=273#event_info_273 Eurovision 1956]. Eurovision.tv. Retrieved on 24 May 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528052507/http://www.eurovision.tv/index/main?page=66&event=273#event_info_273 |date=May 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n* \nThere have been 64 contests, with one winner each year except the tied [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969|1969 contest]], which had four. Twenty-seven countries have won the contest. [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Switzerland]] won the first contest in 1956. The country with the highest number of wins is [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Ireland]], with seven. The only person to have won more than once as performer is Ireland's [[Johnny Logan (singer)|Johnny Logan]], who performed \"[[What's Another Year]]\" in 1980 and \"[[Hold Me Now (Johnny Logan song)|Hold Me Now]]\" in 1987. Logan is also one of only five songwriters to have written more than one winning entry (\"[[Hold Me Now (Johnny Logan song)|Hold Me Now]]\" 1987 and \"[[Why Me? (Linda Martin song)|Why Me?]]\" 1992, performed by [[Linda Martin]]).<ref>O'Connor, John Kennedy. The Eurovision Song Contest \u2013 The Official History. Carlton Books, UK. 2007 {{ISBN|978-1-84442-994-3}}</ref> This unique distinction makes Logan the only person to have three Eurovision victories to his/her credit, as either singer, songwriter or both. The other four songwriters with more than one winning entry to their credit are, [[Willy van Hemert]] (Netherlands, 1957 and 1959), Yves Dessca (Monaco, 1971 and Luxembourg, 1972), [[Rolf L\u00f8vland]] (Norway, 1985 and 1995) and [[Brendan Graham]] (Ireland, 1994 and 1996).\n\nWinning the Eurovision Song Contest provides a unique opportunity for the winning artist(s) to capitalise on their success and surrounding publicity by launching or furthering their international career during their singing years. However, throughout the history of the contest, relatively few of these artists have gone on to be huge international stars. The most notable winning Eurovision artists whose career was directly launched into the spotlight following their win were the members of [[ABBA]], who won the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974|1974 contest]] for Sweden with their song \"[[Waterloo (ABBA song)|Waterloo]]\". ABBA went on to be one of the most successful bands of its time.<ref>[[BBC News]] (6 December 2005). [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4502670.stm ABBA's Bjorn says no to reunion]. Retrieved on 15 March 2008.</ref> Another notable winner who subsequently achieved international fame and success was [[C\u00e9line Dion]], who won the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1988|1988 contest]] for Switzerland with the song \"[[Ne partez pas sans moi]]\".\n\nSince 2008, the winner has been awarded an official winner's trophy of the Eurovision Song Contest. The trophy is a handmade piece of sandblasted glass in the shape of a 1950s [[microphone]].<ref name=\"Trophy\">{{Cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/about/trophy/|title=Trophy|website=Eurovision Song Contest|language=en|access-date=31 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kostaboda.co.uk/eurovision-song-contest/|title=Eurovision Crystal Trophy|website=[[Kosta Glasbruk|Kosta Boda]]|language=en|access-date=31 May 2019}}</ref> The song writers and composers of the winning entry receive smaller versions of the trophy.<ref name=\"Trophy\" /> The original design was created by Kjell Engman of [[Kosta Glasbruk|Kosta Boda]], who specialises in glass art.<ref name=\"Trophy\" />\n\n== Winners by year ==\n{{see also|List of Eurovision Song Contest winning songwriters}}\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\" data-sort-type=\"usLongDate\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\"| Song\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\"| Performer\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\"| Language\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\"| Points\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"autorowspan\"| Margin\n! scope=\"col\" c