al intelligibility|mutually intelligible]] and often considered varieties of a single language, [[Serbo-Croatian]]. However, they are listed separately in Eurovision statistics.</ref>\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989]]\n|[[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]\n|-\n|[[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]]<ref group=\"N\" name=\"wilddances\">This song was partially sung in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]].</ref>\n|[[Ukraine]]<ref group=\"N\" name=\"wilddances\">This song was partially sung in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]].</ref>\n|-\n|[[Serbian language|Serbian]]<ref group=\"N\" name=\"serbo-croatian\">Croatian (the language of the 1989 winning song) and Serbian (the language of the 2007 winning song) are fully [[mutual intelligibility|mutually intelligible]] and often considered varieties of a single language, [[Serbo-Croatian]]. However, they are listed separately in Eurovision statistics.</ref>\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]]\n|[[Serbia]]\n|-\n|[[Crimean Tatar language|Crimean Tatar]]\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]]<ref group=\"N\" name=\"1944_(song)|1944\">This song was partially sung in [[Crimean Tatar language|Crimean Tatar]].</ref>\n|[[Ukraine]]<ref group=\"N\" name=\"1944_(song)|1944\">This song was partially sung in [[Crimean Tatar language|Crimean Tatar]].</ref>\n|-\n|[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]]\n|[[Portugal]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Photogallery ==\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nFile:Lys Assia (1957).jpg|[[Lys Assia]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1956|1956]] contest for Switzerland.\nFile:Eurovision Song Contest 1958 - Corry Brokken.png|[[Corry Brokken]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1957|1957]] contest for the Netherlands.\nFile:Eurovision Song Contest 1958 - Andr\u00e9 Claveau.png|[[Andr\u00e9 Claveau]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1958|1958]] contest for France.\nFile:Dam tot Dam race , Teddy S